result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Jesse D Lewis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Maintain full-time work, school or combination of the two.
To commit no further criminal acts during the period of the agreement.

Comply with any and all orders contained in Door County Famil Case 09-FA-52, as they relate to custody, place and visitation with the child E.E.T., DOB 1/22/2009. Comply with any and all rules of probtion and successfully complete any term of probation ordered as a part of this case.   Defendant shall provide a copy of this agreement, along with the Criminal Complaint, to any counselor and sign any and all releases necessary to allow the counselor (or agency) to report compliance or lack thereof to the District Attorney's Office.  Any assessments done without this agreement and the Criminal Complaint(s) being supplied to the counselor will be considered violations of this agreement and not be accepted.  This agreement may be revoked or the defendant may have to complete a new assessment.

Defendant shall pay restitution to his probation agent in the form of cash or money order (no personal check will be accepted), on behalf of the victim. All restitution must be paid in full by the end of the term of probation supervision.
To pay restitution plus any statutorily authorized surcharges.

To pay the costs of the action.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. To pay supervision fees as ordered by the Dept. of Corrections.

Complete any counseling, evaluations, programs and assessments as appropriate resulting from the Department's COMPAS assessment. Comply with any/all orders regarding custody, placement and visitation contained in Door County Family Case 09-FA-52.

Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement

Defendant Jesse D Lewis in court with attorney Gregory A. Gerbers.  Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Minute sheet. State files amended Information adding Ct. 2, Obstructing charge. Court reviews added charge and max. penalties. Defense waives reading of the Information, is ready to conclude matter today.   State gives plea agreement.  Court questions defendant on change of plea.  Rights/elements/max. penalties reviewed with defendant.  Defendant enters no contest plea to Cts. 1 & 2.  Defense stipulates to factual basis to accept plea.  Court finds pleas made freely, knowingly and voluntarily, accepts plea, and finds guilty of Ct. 2. Court withholds accepting of the plea on Ct. 1 to allow defendant time to complete terms of Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement.  Court reviews collateral consequences with defendant if he should be found guilty of the felony charge. Upon successful completion of all terms of agreement, State will, after 2 years, move to dismiss Ct. 1 and matter can be disposed by written stipulation. Court reviews DAGPA with defendant, approves and signs agreement. Bond remains in effect regarding Ct. 1.  Deferred prosecution agreement hearing scheduled for April 24, 2017 at 11:45 am.
Defense waives reading of Information and enters not guilty plea.  Bond remains as is.
